@fantastic9449 It’s the fact that that’s the story that was decided on. In my opinion, it’s not natural, like how none of the examples I mentioned have felt natural. Someone behind the scenes chose that story not because it was the best story, but because there’s a strong female up and comer who wants (who the writers want) to be the main lead that’s already established. I can’t tell you how many times in movies and shows just in the last couple of years I’ve heard a new female counterpart of an already established male character talk about how she’s studied every last thing there is to know about whatever the main character does, how she’s obsessed with becoming the exact thing the main protagonist is, how she’s mastered so much of the necessary things to master in order to get that position, and each time the protagonist is always caught off guard and extremely impressed with this person. 

That’s my point. A few times? Sure, why not? Countless movies and shows doing the exact same thing with countless already established characters? Well, I don’t know what else to tell you, people will and have lose/lost interest. Its become boring already. And it’s clear it’s just being pushed because of whatever weird agenda is on the bulletin board today. 

It’s the same argument for the whole “black superman” thing. Why not just make a new character? Wouldn’t that be the most diverse thing you could do? Instead of altering the appearance of beloved established characters, or giving them little sidekicks that are just like them, and just as good as them in the story, why not give them their entire own character and movie/show?

